# 📌 Understanding `async` vs `defer` in JavaScript

When loading JavaScript in the browser, using `async` and `defer` helps avoid blocking HTML parsing and improves performance.

---

## 🧩 Example (with inline explanation)

```html
<!-- Async -->
<script src="async.js" async></script>

<!-- Defer -->
<script src="defer.js" defer></script>
```

```js
// async.js
console.log("Async script executed");

// defer.js
console.log("Defer script executed");
```

---

## 🖼️ Visual Diagram

```text
Legend:
🟩 HTML Parsing   🟦 Script Download   🟥 Script Execution

Default:
🟩🟩🟩🟥🟥🟩🟩🟩
(HTML stops → script runs → resumes)

Async:
🟩🟩🟩🟦🟩🟦🟥🟩
(download in parallel, executes anytime)

Defer:
🟩🟩🟩🟦🟩🟦🟩🟥
(download in parallel, executes after parsing)
```

---

## ⚡ async

```html
<script src="script.js" async></script>
```

### How it works:

* Script downloads in parallel with HTML parsing
* Executes immediately after download
* Pauses HTML parsing during execution

### ❗ Key Point:

* Execution order is NOT guaranteed

---

## 🕓 defer

```html
<script src="script.js" defer></script>
```

### How it works:

* Script downloads in parallel
* Executes AFTER HTML parsing completes
* Executes in order

### ❗ Key Point:

* Safe to use with DOM

---

## 🔄 Execution Flow

```text
Async:
HTML parsing → continues
↓
Script downloads
↓
Executes immediately (may interrupt parsing)

Defer:
HTML parsing → continues
↓
Script downloads
↓
Executes AFTER parsing (in order)
```

---

## 🧠 When to Use

* Use async → Independent scripts (ads, analytics)
* Use defer → DOM-related or dependent scripts

---

## ⚠️ Common Mistake

```html
<script src="lib.js" async></script>
<script src="app.js" async></script>
```

👉 `app.js` might run before `lib.js`

---

## 🏁 Summary

* Default `<script>` → blocks HTML (avoid)
* async → fast but unordered
* defer → safe and recommended

---

### 💡 Rule to remember

* Use `defer` by default
* Use `async` only when order doesn’t matter
